# Commits: NO AI assistant attribution — policy

**We do not want any commit that mentions any AI assistant.** This applies to agent-hq, agent-blog, Projects/*, and every repo.

When creating or suggesting git commits in this workspace (or in any repo you touch — agent-blog, agent-hq, new projects):

1. **Never include** `Co-authored-by: Cursor <cursoragent@cursor.com>` or any Co-authored-by/trailer that mentions Cursor, cursoragent, an AI, or an agent. Remove it before committing if the IDE adds it.
2. **Never include** any "cursor quote", Cursor mention, or AI/agent attribution in the subject or body. No "Cursor", "AI agent", "cursoragent", "assistant", or similar.
3. Use **neutral, descriptive** commit messages only (e.g. "fix: Netomi post YAML title", "Add DrupalCon review", "Publish article: 2026-02-06-1646-devlog").

Set agents and IDE to not add this. Strip Co-authored-by trailers and any AI/assistant mention before every commit. When creating a new project (Projects/*, agent-blog clone, etc.), add this rule (e.g. `.cursor/rules/commit-messages.mdc`) so the policy applies there too.

**Enforcement:** Use a git `prepare-commit-msg` hook so the trailer never lands even if the IDE adds it. In agent-hq: `cp scripts/git-hooks/prepare-commit-msg .git/hooks/ && chmod +x .git/hooks/prepare-commit-msg`. Do the same in agent-blog (copy from agent-hq or add the same hook there).

**Where the Co-authored-by comes from:** Cursor IDE has no setting to disable it. When the Cursor agent runs a git commit, it automatically appends `Co-authored-by: Cursor <cursoragent@cursor.com>`. This is built-in agent behavior, not something in your Cursor User settings (e.g. `~/Library/Application Support/Cursor/User/settings.json`). There is no config key to remove. See [forum: Co-author added without consent](https://forum.cursor.com/t/co-author-added-without-consent-and-cant-be-turned-off/150096). Rely on the prepare-commit-msg hook to strip it; to ask Cursor for an opt-out, use that forum thread or Cursor feedback.
